{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526770"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14153"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14153"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.55,0.2,0.02,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102063"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6836"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84517"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"3809"},{"type":"tags","id":"3884"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8143"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35440"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102063"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a painless lump in her right breast. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm firm, non-tender mass in the upper outer quadrant of the right breast. There are no palpable axillary lymph nodes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA mammogram and ultrasound are performed, followed by a core needle biopsy. The pathology report shows a high-grade invasive ductal carcinoma that is negative for oestrogen receptors, progesterone receptors, and demonstrates no HER2 over-expression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radiation therapy","Neoadjuvant chemotherapy","Immediate mastectomy","Hormonal therapy","Lumpectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been diagnosed with triple-negative breast cancer, characterised by the oestrogen receptor-negative, progesterone receptor-negative, and HER2-negative biopsy specimen. Triple-negative breast cancer typically has a more aggressive clinical course and poorer prognosis compared to other breast cancer subtypes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeoadjuvant chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management for this patient. For triple-negative breast cancers, especially those larger than 2 cm or with positive lymph nodes, neoadjuvant chemotherapy is often recommended. This approach can help shrink the tumour before surgery, potentially allowing for breast-conserving surgery instead of mastectomy. It also provides an opportunity to assess the tumour\u0027s response to chemotherapy, which can provide prognostic information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormonal therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective in this case because the tumour is negative for both oestrogen and progesterone receptors. Hormonal therapies such as tamoxifen or aromatase inhibitors are only effective against hormone receptor-positive breast cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used after surgery (either lumpectomy or mastectomy) to reduce the risk of local recurrence. It is not the initial treatment of choice for newly diagnosed breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgery, including \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate mastectomy \u003C/strong\u003Eor\u003Cstrong\u003E lumpectomy,\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically the first steps for triple-negative breast cancers of this size. While mastectomy may eventually be necessary, neoadjuvant chemotherapy is often preferred initially to potentially shrink the tumour before surgery. This approach may allow for breast-conserving surgery in some cases and provides important prognostic information based on the tumour\u0027s response to chemotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of triple-negative breast cancer typically involves a multidisciplinary approach, including surgery, chemotherapy, and often radiation therapy. The specific treatment plan may vary based on factors such as tumour size, lymph node involvement, and the patient\u0027s overall health and preferences.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Triple-negative breast cancer is characterised by being oestrogen receptor-negative, progesterone receptor-negative, and HER2-negative.","Triple-negative breast cancer typically has a poorer prognosis compared to other breast cancer subtypes.","Neoadjuvant chemotherapy is often recommended for triple-negative breast cancer to reduce tumour size before surgery."],"references":["Giordano SH, Franzoi MAB, Temin S, et al. Updated ASCO guidelines for patients with HER2-positive breast cancer. Cancer. 2023;129(1):10. doi:10.1002/cncr.34588. Available at: https://acsjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/cncr.34588"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84517"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84517","links":{"self"